RStudy of Training Metrics on Operational Effectiveness

To investigate the potential correlation between operational effectiveness and pipeline training completion, we first compiled several salient statistics about individuals within the company - i.e. grade, time in grade, time on station, SANS Courses, common cyber certifications, pipeline training complete, JQR/JQS complete, education, etc. We then polled across team leadership to get their perceptions of operational impact and effectiveness for each of the personnel on their respective teams. To do this, we asked them to assess each person on a 1-10 scale, with the following word descriptions to guide feedback: 1 - Negative Value, I would be better without. 3- No value, I could lose tomorrow and nothing would change 5 - Minimal value, I would need to replace his work roles but it shouldn’t be hard 7 - Large value, highly qualified, there are few who could replace him 9 - Immense value, absolute star and center of gravity who could not be replaced 10 - Person is a Unicorn - only person in the Army doing what they are doing

As we can see, it is about a company’s worth of personnel, with a very complete data set. This is, however, a rather small data set for most machine learning and statistics

Next, we will analyze some of the common training measures and usual measures of personnel effectivess and their correlation to operational effectiveness. We will use a Spearmen correlation coefficient for this measure, as the response variable is ordinal (i.e. quality ranking from 1 to 10).

ct1 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, quality$PipelineComplete, method ="spearman")
ct2 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, quality$JQR.JQSComplete, method ="spearman")
ct3 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, quality$AnySANS, method ="spearman")
ct4 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, quality$AnyCert, method ="spearman")
ct5 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, quality$TimeonStation, method ="spearman")
ct6 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, quality$TimeinGrade, method ="spearman")
ct7 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, quality$Badged, method ="spearman")
names1 =c("Pipeline", "JQR/JQS", "Any SANS Courses", "Any Certs", "Time on Station", "Time in Grade", "Badged")
barplot(c(ct1,ct2,ct3,ct4,ct5, ct6, ct7), names.arg = names1, main = "Spearman Correlation between Common Measures and Operational
        Quality", xlab="Common Measures of Individual Effectiveness", ylab = "Correlation to Operational Effectiveness")

library(corrplot)
corMat <- cor(data.frame(quality[, c("OperationalQuality", "PipelineComplete", "JQR.JQSComplete", "AnySANS", "AnyCert", 
                                     "TimeonStation", "TimeinGrade", "Badged")]))
corrplot(corMat, method = "color")

As can be seen, nothing is strongly correlated with operational effectiveness. The only strong correlation is between pipeline complete and JQR/JQS complete; this should make sense given that the two often go hand-in-hand. Time on Station and being Badged have the most correlation to Operational Quality

Having looked at some common measures, lest investigate various possible sub categroies for their salience in operational effectives. We will start with rank:

cr1 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, model.matrix(~quality$Rank-1), method ="spearman")
names2 <- c("1LT", "1SG", "CIV", "CPT", "CW2", "CW3", "CW4", "LTC", "MAJ", "MSG", "PFC", "SFC", "SGT", "SPC", "SSG", "W01")
barplot(cr1[1:16], names.arg = names2, main = "Spearman Correlation between Ranks and Operational
        Quality", xlab="Rank", ylab = "Correlation to Operational Effectiveness")

In this case, it appears that some ranks do have some moderately strong correlation, to include negative correlation. In particular, it seems enlisted and NCO ranks are usually negatively correlated with operational effectiveness, while officer ranks are positively correlated.

Now, lets look at the possible correlations between rank and operational effectivesness

cr5 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, model.matrix(~quality$WorkRole-1), method ="spearman")
names6 <- c("1SG", "ASIA", "CND MGR", "Commander", "CYBER OPS NCO", "CYBER OPS SPEC", "CYBER OPS TECH", "Deputy",
            "DNEA", "EA", "ION", "LA", "NCOIC", "NET INFRA SVC SPEC", "Orderly NCO", "OTDA", "Planner", "SECURITY ANALYST",
            "SEL", "SYSTEMS ARCHITECT", "TAR", "TDNA", "Team Lead", "Training NCO")
barplot(cr5[1:24], names.arg = names6, main = "Spearman Correlation between Work Role and Operational
        Quality", xlab="Work Role", ylab = "Correlation to Operational Effectiveness")

So, it seems work roles does have some impacts on operational effectiveness. In particular, administartive roles like Orderly Room or Training Room are quite negatively correlated to operational effectiveness.

Next, lets investigate if having a degree - to include type, and where the degree was obtained from - have any correlation to operational effectiveness.

cr2 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, model.matrix(~quality$Degree-1), method ="spearman")
names3 <- c("associates", "bachelors", "masters", "none")
barplot(cr2[1:4], names.arg = names3, main = "Spearman Correlation between Highest Degree Held and Operational
        Quality", xlab="Highest Degree Held", ylab = "Correlation to Operational Effectiveness")

cr3 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, model.matrix(~quality$DegreeType-1), method ="spearman")
names4 <- c("CS", "EE", "IT", "Math", "non-STEM", "none", "STEM-Other")
barplot(cr3[1:7], names.arg = names4, main = "Spearman Correlation between Type of Degree Held and Operational
        Quality", xlab="Type of Degree Held", ylab = "Correlation to Operational Effectiveness")

cr4 <- cor(quality$OperationalQuality, model.matrix(~quality$UndergraduateUniversity-1), method ="spearman")
names5 <- c("none", "Not USMA", "Online", "USMA")
barplot(cr4[1:4], names.arg = names5, main = "Spearman Correlation between Undergraduate University and Operational
        Quality", xlab="Undergraduate University", ylab = "Correlation to Operational Effectiveness")

There are some rather intersting results. First, having no degree is negatively correlated with Operational effectiveness in every case. In other words, degrees are important in some respect to operational effectiveness. Also interesting is that CS, Math, and Non-STEM degrees are positively correlated, while EE and IT are negatively correlated. This could be a result of the small number of people within the data set possessing these degress and there operational effectiveness is likely decreased for other reasons.

All in all, while there are some interesting trends, correlation between operational effectiveness and the various factors studied here are generally low - highest correlation is under 0.5. Thus, there is more than likely a confluence of factors that are significant (i.e. officer, with a degree in CS may correlate highly) and that the metrics we are using, like Pipeline complete are not representative of actual operational effectivness of a person

As a brief aside, we will alo take a look at a correlation matrix for SANS and certification courses

corMat <- cor(data.frame(quality[, c("OperationalQuality", "SEC508", "SEC408", "SEC401.GSEC.", "SEC501..GCED.", 
                                     "FOR500.GCFE.", "SEC504..GCIH.", "SEC503..GCIA.", "SEC560..GPEN.", "SEC301.GISF.",
                                     "CISSP", "OSCP", "A.", "SEC.", "NET.", "CEH", "CCNA")]))
corrplot(corMat, method = "color")

Not surprisngly, SANS courses tend to correlate, as to SEC+, NET+, and CEH. However, none of the correlate strongly to Operational Quality. In fact, SEC508, SEC408, and CISSP are slightly negatively correlated.

Now, we would like to see if we can produce any kind of predictive model for operational quality. To do this, we will first need to remove some of the less important columns to reduce the dimensionality of the data set; we do not have enough data to succesfully fit a model using all of the possible feature vectors.

linCols <- c("OperationalQuality", "Rank", "TimeinGrade", "TimeonStation", "Badged", "WorkRole", "Degree", "DegreeType",
             "UndergraduateUniversity", "AnySANS", "AnyCert", "JQR.JQSComplete")
linearQuality <- quality[linCols]

We will begin by investigating a linear regression model. This model assumes statistical independence among the feature vectors, and a numerical - as oppsoed to categorical - response variable (which, in this case is not structly true).

model1 <- lm(OperationalQuality ~., data=linearQuality)
summary(model1)

Next, we will simplify the data a little and try a logistic regression. We will first transform the reponse variable from 1-10 score to just a ‘good’ or ‘bad’ score whne it comes to operational effectiveness. We will use the middle value of 5 as the cut off; everything below 5 will become 0 (bad) and everything baove 5 will become 1 (good). We will also break the data set into a ‘train’ and ’test; data set to get a better picture of how accurate the model could be on new, unknown data - and thus a measure of its predicitive power.

Now, we will investigate a model better suited for categorical data and for dealing with categorical feature vectors: A Catergorical And Regression Tree (CART) model. This model will breakdown the salient feature vectors into a decision tree to allow us to not only predict future values, but also show us what values are salient in determining the response vectors, which is in this case operational effectiveness. We will not cross validate the model with k-manifolds to set the number of leafs in the tree and the complexity of the model because we simply do not have enough data to split into meaningful manifolds. So, we will just use the defualt settings for the rpart function.

set.seed(9)
split = sample.split(linearQuality$OperationalQuality, SplitRatio = 0.8)
linTrain = subset(linearQuality, split==TRUE)
linTest = subset(linearQuality, split==FALSE)
library(rpart)
library(rpart.plot)
qualityTree <- rpart(OperationalQuality ~., data =linTrain, method="class")
prp(qualityTree)

If we look at this model and follow the tree, rnak and work role seem to be the most important factors when looking at qulaity. The highest quality that can be see on the tree, an 8, is an officer (CPT, CW2, CW3) or NCO (MSG or SGT) that is not in certain work roles like EA, DNEA, and others. Of particular, pipeline training completion and certifications do not feature in the tree at all.

Next, lets investigate its predictive power with a confusion matrix.

PredictCART = predict(qualityTree, newdata = linTest, type = "class")

Looking at the confusion matrix, it does not look like there is much gain on the CART model. This is likely becuase there is simply not enough data to run a significant amount of random trees to make a good random forest model.

All in all, the CART technique shows decent results and very good promise for a future model for discerning what factors are salient in opertionally effective Soldiers and Civilians.

This brief investigation has some key findings worth note and very much worth future investigation: 1. trained and qualified means little to nothing for an invidiuals actual operational effectiveness 2. Certs like Net+ and Sec+, and SANS courses, also mean little to nothing for an invidiuals actual operational effectiveness 3. Education matters - having a degree correlates to operational effectiveness in every case 4. Some work roles matter more than others for operational effectiveness’

Based on these findings, it is reasonable to conclude that measureing readiness for our teams based on FT & FQ numbers along with manning numbers is a mistake; these metrics matter little on the individual level and likely matter even less in the aggregate. We need a far more comprehensive study of what ‘quality’ and ‘readiness’ is actually realted to if we are to truly evaluate ourselves and make beneficial decisions for the force.
